Map each SWOT quadrant to a time-boxed initiative: Strengths → exploit immediately (Days 1–30), Weaknesses → mitigate with targeted fixes (Days 31–60), Opportunities → pursue with small experiments (Days 31–60), Threats → build defenses or contingency plans (Days 61–90). Start by ranking each item by impact × feasibility to identify your top 3 per quadrant. Days 1–30: leverage top Strengths to generate quick wins and establish baseline metrics. Days 31–60: assign owners to the top 2 Weaknesses with measurable remediation targets; simultaneously launch one low-risk Opportunity pilot with a defined success criterion. Days 61–90: operationalize the pilot if metrics hit threshold, and deploy the top Threat mitigation (process change, partnership, or buffer stock). Each initiative needs an owner, a single KPI, and a weekly 15-min review cadence. At Day 90, re-run the SWOT with new data to close the loop and feed the next quarter.
